On 3/6/20 3:44 PM, Noel Chiappa wrote:
> a pipe is a FIFO.

Hum....

Does that mean that I should be able to replace pipes in my shell=20
commands with a collections of FIFOs?  I'm not saying that I would want=20
to.  Well, at least not beyond an academic exercise.

> RAND ports just allowed (effectively) a pipe to have a name in the=20
> file system.

I've got to admit that this statement, particularly the first two words, =

caused me a lot of trouble.  The first few times I read it I kept=20
thinking that RAND ported something from another platform /=20
architecture.  I now think it effectively means "(the) port (solution)=20
from RAND".  Suffice it to say that many of the emails in this thread=20
didn't make sense with my first, seemingly incorrect, understanding, and =

made a LOT more sense with my second, seemingly correct, understanding.

> The implementation of both is pretty straight-forward. A pipe is=20
> just a file which has a maximum length, after which the writer is=20
> blocked. A port is just a pipe (it uses the pipe code) whose inode=20
> appears in the file system.

Intriguing.

It is interesting learning the history of things that I've taken for=20
granted for 25 years.

This thread aligns quite well with some external reading that I've done=20
trying to learn more about file descriptors and redirection.  TL;DR:=20
The redirection symbols (syntax) weren't doing what I thought they were=20
doing.  I now believe that they change values of variables used for I/O. =

  Much like DD statements in JCL.



--=20
Grant. . . .
unix || die


